<br />
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Alright, first things first:<br />
<br />
Start with Legolas and Arwen (but for God&#39;s sake, keep them face down till the bidding&#39;s done!).  Bid low, two at the most, because this deck can work both ways.  Obviously the ideal would be that you opponent wins the bid with three or higher and then plays the Prancing Pony.  If, however, something funny comes up, we have a safety valve.  His name is Ulaire Nelya.  There are four of him. Hopefully one of these will find its way into your hand on the draw, because if it does, your first three sites are set.<br />
<br />
Okay, suppose your opponent goes first, but does not play the Prancing Pony.  He does his thing at site one, and moves to your site two, Breeland Forest.  Breeland Forest is a relatively harmless site two...after all, everyone hates those darn stealth events anyway.  So, hopefully, your opponent sees Legolas and Arwen, thinks &quot;Elf deck&quot;, sees Breeland Forest and thinks anything but &quot;Nazgul deck&quot;, and continues on unsuspecting to site 3.  (Side Note:  Don&#39;t drop anything at site two unless they give you an unreal amount of twilight!)  Then, at the Fords, you have a chance to drop multiple Nazgul upon your unsuspecting foe.  Ouch.  If one of those is Nelya, replace their site one with the Prancing Pony.  Perfect.<br />
<br />
If, however, your opponent chooses to go second, proceed like normally, bring out the Pony and pull Aragorn.  Double move into site three if at all possible, b/c this will force most decks into doing the same to keep up.  As you can see, the point is that if they double move into the Fords, someone&#39;s going to get hammered.<br />
<br />
(On a side note, an explanation of the reason for the rare Frodo:  the uncommon one&#39;s so bad that it&#39;s better just to play the rare to fake having a bounder in your deck somewhere.  Yes, he is that bad; what, you were going to exert Legolas to heal him???)<br />
<br />
Basically, this is a beat down Nazgul deck after that, and there&#39;s not many decks that can stand up to it if you get Morgul Gates at the right time.  The Witch-King coupled with anyone is just brutal.  <br />
<br />
As for the fellowship, I went for versatility here.  With the three No Stranger to the Shadows coupled with three rangers, it can choke the twilight at times, in addition to being nearly impossible to take down if allowed to spread its wings.  Aragorn is a potential 12 strength, 5 vitality, with 4 archery exertions to spare, while Boromir can be as high as 11 strength.  With Arwen at a 9 against Nazgul (11 with Gwemegil) and 3 Ranger&#39;s Versatility, handling a Nazgul deck is made much easier.  The Power According to His Stature x2 should be a safety valve against the moria swarms, together with the directed archery, and the great healing ability of Aragorn KIE and 3 athelas is wonderful against those darn damage +1 uruks or against a hate/orc bowmen/under the watchful eye sauron deck.  In short, this is a deck that can account for many different types of opposition and if played right, can dominate. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php?PHPSESSID=c0325b5c85b55c5f65d4f8fa8d32136d">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=21111&PHPSESSID=c0325b5c85b55c5f65d4f8fa8d32136d"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=21111&PHPSESSID=c0325b5c85b55c5f65d4f8fa8d32136d" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=c0325b5c85b55c5f65d4f8fa8d32136d">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
